I only have experience with free resources, paid ones might be good though I can't buy them.   So you could use Khan Academy's or Chadsprep's free Chemistry courses on their site or YT channel, alternatively you can use UC Irvine's and MIT OpenCourseWare lectures on Chemistry which goes even to Graduate level stuff, they all offer hundreds of videos in the Chemistry topic and are so far the best resource I've found for videos. You can use The Organic Chemistry Tutor's playlists to explain some harder stuff in a quick way, like difficult reactions or topics where you already know the theory behind it and you just want to make calculations. Then you can learn about Organic Chemistry and the reactions that can happen, learn about a little bit of quantum chemistry etc. You can use your knowledge in Organic Chemistry to either go for studies in the Biochemical field or Physical Chemistry, perhaps if you want to know how different materials can be used and what their properties are, or continue your studies in Inorganic Chemistry.   Personally I don't have any experience with Physical Chemistry, but yeah. If you want a free, open-source textbook then you can use Libretexts for any field, even Engineering. Somewhere along the way you can take MIT 3.091SC Solid State Chemistry to learn things like how transistors and conductance/electric current work, as well as crystallography. If you want to make experiments, you'll want to get a lab manual for experiments and then start off buying compounds and utensils for them, just make sure to follow the safety guides and know exactly what compounds you're working with.   I saw nobody replied, but if anybody wants to look into chemistry, these are the best resources I could find in my search. Chemistry is a big and growing field.
